Oh, you are right, I did not even think of it, thanks for pointing this out...

But I do not see how checking for `stream in ...` will prevent the edge case of user replacing `sys.stderr` with a non-tty stream (on Pycharm). 😕 

In my opinion, as we are wrapping a broken `sys.__stderr__` stream, we should take the opportunity to fix it. Something like this:

```python
class StreamWrapper(object):
    ...

    def isatty(self):
        return is_a_tty(self.__wrapped)
```

It seems to fix all the edge cases we discussed, what do you think?

You added `@wraps` which fixes the name/docstring problem, but just re-copying this here as a note to my future self, in case we need to improve the performance of this code later on:

This will cause us to need to construct a new function every time we want to make an API call.

To be more economical, we could try something like this:

```python
class APICallWrapper(object):
    def __init__(self, func_that_makes_an_api_call, instance=None, owner=None):
        ...
        self._instance = instance
        self._owner = owner

    def __get__(self, instance, owner):
        return self.__class__(func_that_makes_an_api_call, instance=instance, owner=owner)

    def __call__(*args, **kwargs):
        ...
```

As another idea, we can consider using https://pypi.python.org/pypi/wrapt to power the decorator, so that we don't have to think at all about the descriptor. Though that would introduce its own slowness.

